4) Optional Class (VERY Important)

Optional class is container object used to avoid NullPointerException.
It helps when value may be null.

Difference between of(), ofNullable(), empty()?

✅ Answer:
Optional.of(value) → throws NullPointerException if value is null
Optional.ofNullable(value) → safe even if value is null
Optional.empty() → returns empty optional

   Optional<String> a = Optional.ofNullable(null); // OK
// Optional<String> b = Optional.of(null); // ❌ NPE


6) Stream API (Most Asked)

✅ What is Stream?
A Stream is used to process data from a collection (List/Set) in a clean way.

📌 Stream does NOT store data
✅ It only processes data.

Why use Stream?
less code
clean logic
easy filtering/mapping
no manual loops needed

Example List:
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4,5,6);

With stream, we can say:
filter even numbers
convert them
print/store result

✅ Stream basic structure :
collection.stream()
    .intermediateOperations()
    .terminalOperation();

---
 7) Intermediate Operations (Lazy)

✅ What are Intermediate Operations?
Intermediate operations are steps in between.
📌 They return a Stream again so we can chain more steps.
📌 They are lazy → they don’t execute until terminal operation is called.

Common Intermediate Operations
✅ filter() → select elements
✅ map() → change elements
✅ sorted() → sort
✅ distinct() → remove duplicates
✅ limit() → take first few
✅ skip() → skip first few

Example
import java.util.*;
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4,5,6);

        list.stream()
            .filter(x -> x % 2 == 0)
            .map(x -> x * x)
            .forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}
---
8) Terminal Operations (Eager)

✅ What are Terminal Operations?
They end the stream and give final result.

Common Terminal operations:
✅ forEach() → print/perform action
✅ collect() → store result into List/Set/Map
✅ count() → count elements
✅ reduce() → sum/product
✅ min(), max()

Example
import java.util.*;
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(10,20,30,40);

        long c = nums.stream().count(); // terminal
        System.out.println(c); // 4
    }
}

